Diagnosis: The males of this species can be recognised by the short narrow embolus with narrow base and transverse distal section of the coil with a slightly curved, distally directed tip (
Fig. 165
). Females have widely separated lateral copulatory openings that are curved towards the anterior (towards posterior in
C. montana
sp. nov.
) and narrow copulatory ducts with a distinct lateral loop (broad and directly transverse in
C. montana
sp. nov.
) (
Figs 180, 181
).

Remarks: The paratype female is in relatively poor condition and all of the legs but one (left leg IV) are broken off and both pairs of anterior legs are missing (
Fig. 161
). The body of the specimen is, however, good enough for most of the measurements to be provided in the description.

Distribution: Only known from two montane localities in Cameroon (
Fig. 182
).
